caption: The perfect balance of exquisite, old-world charm and cozy cafe around the corner in this beautiful restaurant, expertly managed by general manager Amy with service second to none. I've had nearly every pasta dish and dessert, and never went wrong with any of them. Amy and her team remember your name and favorite dish, and I can't wait to be able to dine in this intimate and warm restaurant again!
Good taste

Visited the restaurant earlier today for lunch and was impressed with the attentiveness of the server. I had the caprese sandwich on focaccia with prosciutto and it was delicious. My friend had the real meatballs and spaghetti that were absolutely divine. The meatballs were tender and the fresh pasta was top notch. The only drawback of this restaurant is that the  menu is somewhat expensive for lunch, including $6 for a Coca-cola. Overall, I would definitely go back and would recommend it to others. #amanaboutfood

My fiancé and I stopped here for a quick bite after work one day. We just wanted a snack before our commute home. It was a friday night and the place was hoppin, but they were able to find a table for us. Our server was so attentive and kind (I wish I remembered her name!) and all of the support workers were friendly and hardworking as well. We just got a couple of appetizers— the brussel sprouts and cauliflower (I think these are seasonal items) and the amazing meatballs. We also were automatically brought bread and dipping oil. All of the food was delicious. Normally we would like at least salt and pepper in our dipping oil but this oil was so good, it didn’t need any seasoning at all. We were very happy with our experience here and we will definitely be back to one of the locations soon for a full dinner!

I didn't feel this experience was worth the hype  (and question the Bib Gourmand). I truly enjoyed the Stracciatella soup; it's warm, light, and flavorful. The atmosphere is also nice. The downtown location has a well-decorated, rustic vibe, even though the tables are a little close together, making it a little loud.  I ordered the carbonara for my meal. Frankly, I found this dish to be confusing. The choice of pasta was the most confusing part of this dish. The long tubular paccheri pasta would have been well suited for a stuffed pasta or a ragu. When used in a carborna, it lead to a disconnect between the pasta and the pool of sauce around it. The pasta was also too chewy, and not in a pleasant, al dente way.  Even if the correct pasta was used, I would not have enjoyed the use of the unincorporated egg on top of the pasta. The sauce on the pasta was already creamy without the egg (why? sauce should just be egg, cheese and pancetta), so combining the fried egg into the dish made the richness overpowering.

Despite a few highlights from the pasta menu, our overall experience was disappointing. Our party of 3 was seated in a back room at a table so awkwardly positioned that waiter and other diners kept having to ask us to scoot over so they could get through. It took a while for our server to arrive, so by the time he took our drink order, we were prepared to order pasta and entrees. Little did we know this meant the pasta would arrive before even were served our cocktails. On top of this, we had run out of water and no one offered to refill it (in fairness, it would hard to see us in the weird corner they seated us in) so we sat mostly staring at our pasta while it got cold.  It's a shame, because the pasta was quite good--especially the carbonara, which would have been wonderful with the glass of white wine i never had a chance to order.  The short rib entree was just okay--as tender as you'd expect after 72 hours sous vide, but lacking in flavor and mostly fat. Another server who was kind enough to help us after our first server disappeared comped our cocktails and gave us free ice cream for dessert, which was a nice gesture, but the disappointing service and pacing of our meal would discourage me from going back.

Wow! I came here for lunch on a weekday, and I was really satisfied with the food. I had made a reservation for this place, but turns out I didn't really need one as the restaurant was about 2/3 full when I arrived. I got seated promptly and was given the food and drink menus. The food menu was very cute! I debated between the gnocchi with the usual mushroom sauce or switching up to getting it with the lobster / tomatoes / chili sauce (usually paired with the squid ink pasta). I ended up deciding to get the latter, and I love that decision. My food came out very quickly, and the gnocchi was perfectly soft and melty; I kept wondering whether there was cheese in it because it was so melty! They did not skimp on the lobster which I greatly appreciated, and there was an ample amount of tomatoes too. Warm bread was also brought to me along with some olive oil, and I dipped the bread into the pasta sauce. The bread wasn't super great as the crust was hard and the inside wasn't super amazing, just normal. Same with the olive oil. But hey, amazing pasta and portions! Service was also a bit lacking, even though the waiter was friendly and he filled up my water appropriately. Delicious gnocchi, would highly recommend! For $24 pre-tax ($26.40 post-tax), it's a bit pricey for food but acceptable for gnocchi and the great portions.

I just had a late lunch at the Sfoglina downtown location and could not have been happier with my choice.  The food was excellent.  Their take on tiramisu is different from any I've seen before, but was amazing.  I had the pasta special which was large noodles with muscles, lima beans, and mushrooms in a lemon white wine sauce.  Served with rustic bread and olive oil, and it was just the proper amount for a satisfying lunch.  The waitress was friendly, very knowledgeable in the menu, attentive, but did not hover.  This is a place I will definitely go again.

Manufactured fine-dining experience, not to say that's a bad thing. You'll have a very nice meal with very good and frequent service. Friendly staff and good food/desserts. Not a ton of veggie options but usually one or two. Chef knows what he or she is doing.

Great food but as a FYI the portions are pretty small.  The wait staff seemed a bit out of tune and I felt could improve upon their team work.  Tried a few items which were all very good. The whole branzino was amazing and perfectly cooked.  The shells tomato bacon "fume" was another tasty dish but portion was a bit small (ordered the large so the small plate must be super small)  Cocktails were great. Winter orchard and seasonal old fashioned. Both full of flavor.  Desserts were also amazing. Try the chocolate cake and tiramisu! The bomboloni were good too.

If you are looking for the quality of Fiola Mare without the price point, come here to get an amazing fish filet, a light meal or a splurge, with great sharable plates but something for everyone.  For a business lunch or a romantic dinner, this place is spot on.

Great food and wonderful service.  We were here on Valentine's Day, so I probably can't comment on the regular menu, but their V-day menu was amazingly delicious, creative, and clever.  Great place to take that special someone ;)

Recently I had lunch at Casa Luca. It was my first time at this restaurant. I ordered the Atlantic Char and it was delicious. The wait staff are attentive, friendly and professional. Casa Luca is an excellent restaurant for a business meeting or a romantic dinner. I highly recommend Casa Luca.

I am shocked by the number of reviews that rated this restaurant above average.  The wait staff was harried and out of sync throughout our meal. There appeared to be an adequate number of employees but they didn’t work well in unison.  Perhaps some training?  The menu is uninspiring. I’m not sure why many reviews spoke of the authentic nature of the Italian cuisine because most of the menu choices were a combination of ingredients served with pasta.  I’ve never seen such unusual combinations. Churro appetizers?  Sadly, we left hungry as the portions were very small.  Casa Luca misses the mark in so many areas. A few blocks away, RPM is a far better experience or even better a trip to Fiola.

Just another bright star in the Fabio Trabocchi family. I hosted a dinner for 20 at their flagship, Fiola, in the spring and decided to try Casa Luca for a dinner of 20 this winter. The event staff is very helpful in setting up your menu and working through all the details of your visit. The wines were fantastic and reasonably priced.
